    <div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='8246#1271272954'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2010-04-14T19:22:34+00:00">Apr 14, 2010 07:22 PM UTC</time> by <b>Neha Sharma</b><a class="anchor" name="1271272954">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Hello Neha,

we&#39;ve discussed the issue reported in the ticket 5518 with our developer team.
We acknowledge that this is an existing problem in dCache.
Fixing this will cause a global change in the architecture of dCache. So we
cannot fix it in 1.9.5. But we could fix it in the future releases.

best regards,
tanja</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='8246#1268676114'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2010-03-15T18:01:54+00:00">Mar 15, 2010 06:01 PM UTC</time> by <b>Neha Sharma</b><a class="anchor" name="1268676114">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>I&#39;ll open a dCache ticket about it.

On 2/19/2010 2&#58;36 PM, Fengping Hu wrote&#58;
Thanks for your workaround solutions.

But isn&#39;t this a bug. Shall we try to implement a workaround to complicate things or address the root&#58;
which probably is to let implicit space reservation find a link group it can really make reservations rather than just consider the first link group that&#39;s
authorized.

Fengping Hu
Unix Systems Administrator
Rosen Center for Advanced Computing, Purdue University
email&#58;fhu@.... phone&#58; 765-494-0032

Ted Hesselroth wrote&#58;
It will try both, but it is really only looking at them to make the space reservation. LinkGroupAuthorization does come into play to make the implicit
space reservation. I see that /cms is authorized for both. So if you have that credential, it will make the space reservation for the first link group it
considers. When it actually tries to write the file to a path that is in a different link, there is a mismatch which causes the failure you see.

One solution is either to force the desired link group through the LinkGroupAuthorization. Then the user would have to have a non-cms credential to
use the opportunistic storage.

Another is to make an administrative space reservation and tag the directory with that space reservation. That will force the correct link group to be
chosen. See the bottom of this page

<a href='http&#58;//trac.dcache.org/projects/dcache/wiki/manuals/SRM_2.2_Setup' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//trac.dcache.org/projects/dcache/wiki/manuals/SRM_2.2_Setup</a>

which shows how to make the space reservation and the tag. Note there is a typo, the last line should be

echo &#34;123456&#34; &#62; &#34;.(tag)(WriteToken)&#34;

Fengping Hu wrote&#58;
Just added these two tags. But the problem remains.

Like I said in my original email&#58; I can still write to one directory. But not the other.
<div id='show_1617895128' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_1617895128'>
It seems to me the problem is this&#58;
when two(multiple) link groups are available, it(Pool Manager?) would just pick only one link group(it&#39;s ok to just pick one , but it need to pick the right
one).
If the links in this link group can not fulfill the request. It won&#39;t try other available linkgroups.

Fengping Hu
Unix Systems Administrator
Rosen Center for Advanced Computing, Purdue University
email&#58;fhu@.... phone&#58; 765-494-0032

Ted Hesselroth wrote&#58;
I think you may have to tag the directories with these

# echo  &#34;ONLINE&#34; &#62; &#34;.(tag)(AccessLatency)&#34;
# echo  &#34;REPLICA&#34; &#62; &#34;.(tag)(RetentionPolicy)&#34;

according to

<a href='https&#58;//twiki.grid.iu.edu/bin/view/Storage/OpportunisticStorageUse' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>https&#58;//twiki.grid.iu.edu/bin/view/Storage/OpportunisticStorageUse</a>

Fengping Hu wrote&#58;
And I have &#34;srmSpaceManagerEnabled=yes&#34; too

Fengping Hu
Unix Systems Administrator
Rosen Center for Advanced Computing, Purdue University
email&#58;fhu@.... phone&#58; 765-494-0032

Fengping Hu wrote&#58;
I restart everything(&#34;dcache stop&#34; and then &#34;dcache start&#34;) after configuration change since I did this on a test setup.

The resilient pool group names do match in PoolManager.conf and dCacheSetup.

Fengping Hu
Unix Systems Administrator
Rosen Center for Advanced Computing, Purdue University
email&#58;fhu@.... phone&#58; 765-494-0032

Ted Hesselroth wrote&#58;
Also, do you have

srmSpaceManagerEnabled=yes

Were both PoolManager and link groups reloaded after the change?

$ ssh -l admin -c blowfish -p 22223 localhost
admin@localhost&#39;s password&#58;
dCache Admin (VII) (user=admin)

(local) admin &#62; cd PoolManager
(PoolManager) admin &#62; reload -yes
(PoolManager) admin &#62; ..
(local) admin &#62; cd SrmSpaceManager@srm-oursiteDomain
(SrmSpaceManager@srm-cd-oursiteDomain) admin &#62; update link groups
update started
(SrmSpaceManager@srm-oursiteDomain) admin &#62;

If you intend for replica manager to work in the cms pools, in my dCacheSetup it looks like the default name for resilient pools is
#resilientGroupName=ResilientPools

whereas you have

psu create pgroup Resilient-pools

so you may want to change the names to match in PoolManager.conf and dCacheSetup if it is not that way already.

Ted Hesselroth wrote&#58;
Are you using a space token with srmcp, or is srmImplicitSpaceManagerEnabled set to yes in dCacheSetup?

Ted

Fengping Hu wrote&#58;
dcache version&#58; production-1.9.5-8

setup&#58;
Two links are created with each link has it&#39;s own Unit Group configuration.
Two tagged directories are created on the namespace such that&#58;
Link A can write to directory A.
Link B can write to directory B.

At this point I am able to write to both directory A and B with &#34;srmcp&#34; command.

Now create two link groups, with each linkgroup contain one link. Also configure Linkgroup authorization to authorize both linkgroup for my VO.
Supposedly, I should still be able to write to both directory A and B in this case.
But it turns out now I can only write to one directory. &#34;No write pools configured&#34; is the error when I try to write to the other directory.
Isn&#39;t this interesting........

###########################################
Two directories&#58;
/cms$grep &#34;&#34; $(cat &#34;.(tags)()&#34;)
.(tag)(OSMTemplate)&#58;StoreName cms
.(tag)(sGroup)&#58;resilient

/osg$grep &#34;&#34; $(cat &#34;.(tags)()&#34;)
.(tag)(OSMTemplate)&#58;StoreName opportunistic
.(tag)(sGroup)&#58;opensciencegrid

Attached is the PoolManager.conf and LinkGroupauthorization configuration file.
